MR A-Eng. HB 4116
1 ing impacts on household stability, financial inclusion and economic equity, is necessary before any
2 policy changes are enacted; and
3 Whereas establishing a task force to study the role of short-term loans and to explore alterna-
4 tives and safeguards would provide the Legislative Assembly with informed recommendations
5 grounded in the lived experience of Oregon consumers; now, therefore,
6 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
7 SECTION 1. (1) The Task Force on Equitable Access to Short-Term Financial Products
8 is established.
9 (2) The task force consists of 12 members appointed as follows:
10 (a) The President of the Senate shall appoint two nonvoting members from among
11 members of the Senate, one from each caucus.
12 (b) The Speaker of the House of Representatives shall appoint two nonvoting members
13 from among members of the House of Representatives, one from each caucus.
14 (c) The Governor shall appoint eight voting members as follows:
15 (A) Two Oregon residents who have taken out short-term loans in this state;
16 (B) Two members who represent lenders who offer short-term loans;
17 (C) Two members who represent consumer advocacy organizations;
18 (D) One member who represents financial institutions; and
19 (E) The Director of the Department of Consumer and Business Services, or a designee.
20 (3) The task force shall study the following issues:
21 (a) What access Oregonians have to short-term credit and the consequences of changing
22 that level of access;
23 (b) The role short-term loans play in the finances of Oregon residents, including how
24 short-term loans function as a financial bridge for consumers who lack access to traditional
25 credit and the types of emergencies or expenses for which consumers use short-term credit;
26 (c) Features of short-term loans that benefit consumers or that affect consumers’ ability
27 to repay the loans, such as length or term, line size, fee structure and a lack of prepayment
28 penalties;
29 (d) Who in the state needs short-term loan products and who lacks access to traditional
30 credit, including examining urban versus rural households and which populations are dis-
31 proportionately affected by limited access to credit;
32 (e) Potential consequences that might result from restricting or removing access to
33 short-term loan products, including both intended and unintended consequences; and
34 (f) Alternatives, safeguards and policy options for addressing the credit needs of con-
35 sumers in this state, including whether viable substitutes for short-term loans exist at scale
36 and what safeguards could mitigate harm while preserving access to credit.
37 (4) The task force may take testimony, conduct research and perform other tasks to
38 carry out the purpose specified in subsection (3) of this section.
39 (5) A majority of the voting members of the task force constitutes a quorum for the
40 transaction of business.
41 (6) Official action by the task force requires the approval of a majority of the voting
42 members of the task force.
43 (7) The Governor shall select one voting member of the task force to serve as chair-
44 person and another voting member to serve as vice chairperson, for the terms and with the
45 duties and powers necessary for the performance of the functions of the offices as the Gov-
[2]

MR A-Eng. HB 4116
1 ernor determines.
2 (8) If there is a vacancy for any cause, the appointing authority shall make an appoint-
3 ment to become immediately effective.
4 (9) The task force shall meet at times and places specified by the call of the chairperson
5 or of a majority of the voting members of the task force.
6 (10) The task force may adopt rules necessary for the operation of the task force.
7 (11) The task force shall submit a report in the manner provided by ORS 192.245, and
8 may include recommendations for legislation, to an interim committee of the Legislative
9 Assembly related to consumer protection no later than December 15, 2026.
10 (12) The Department of Consumer and Business Services shall provide staff support to
11 the task force.
12 (13) Members of the Legislative Assembly appointed to the task force are nonvoting
13 members of the task force and may act in an advisory capacity only.
14 (14) Members of the task force who are not members of the Legislative Assembly serve
15 as volunteers on the task force and, unless they are qualified members, as defined in ORS
16 292.495, are not entitled to compensation or reimbursement for expenses.
17 (15) All agencies of state government, as defined in ORS 174.111, are directed to assist
18 the task force in the performance of the duties of the task force and, to the extent permitted
19 by laws relating to confidentiality, to furnish information and advice the members of the task
20 force consider necessary to perform their duties.
21 (16) All appointments to the task force made under subsection (2) of this section must
22 be completed by 100 days after adjournment sine die of the 2026 session of the Eighty-third
23 Legislative Assembly.
24 (17) The task force shall have its first meeting on or before 100 days after adjournment
25 sine die of the 2026 session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly.
26 SECTION 2. Section 1 of this 2026 Act is repealed on December 31, 2027.
27 SECTION 3. This 2026 Act takes effect on the 91st day after the date on which the 2026
28 regular session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
